Setting aside whether your model is correct for the moment:

godbrigero:

set R[i, i] to huge value for non-existant values

Instead of doing this, use a different measurement model when measurements are missing. For example, say you have the following model (linear for ease of explanation):

\begin{align*}
\dot{\mathbf{x}} &= \mathbf{A}\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{B}\mathbf{u} \\
\mathbf{y} &= \mathbf{C}\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{D}\mathbf{u}
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\dot{\begin{bmatrix}
x \\ y \\ \theta
\end{bmatrix}} &=
\begin{bmatrix}
0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\ y \\ \theta
\end{bmatrix} +
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
v_x \\ v_y \\ \omega
\end{bmatrix} \\
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\ y \\ \theta
\end{bmatrix} &=
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\ y \\ \theta
\end{bmatrix} +
\begin{bmatrix}
0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
v_x \\ v_y \\ \omega
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

and some 3x3 diagonal matrices for Q and R. If you don’t have a gyro measurement, then just remove it from the measurement model for that timestep:

\mathbf{y} = \mathbf{C}\mathbf{x} + \mathbf{D}\mathbf{u}

\begin{bmatrix}
x \\ y
\end{bmatrix} =
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
x \\ y \\ \theta
\end{bmatrix} +
\begin{bmatrix}
0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
v_x \\ v_y \\ \omega
\end{bmatrix} and use a 2x2 R matrix for the measurements you do have. The EKF update equations handle this fine, and it’s what this overload in WPILib’s EKF class is for.
